title.narrative: MICRONUTRIENT SERVICES

description.narrative: Government authorities at national and subnational level are better able to deliver nutrition services for school-age children, adolescent girls and women, especially in priority regions, which contributes to Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Micronutrients, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Increased coverage of equitable, quality and effective nutrition services among children under five years old.

description.narrative: 1,754,861 pregnant women (82.8 per cent) received Iron and Folic acid Supplementation (IFAS), an increase of 23.8 per cent;as;compared to 2020 as a result of UNICEF’s advocacy for domestic financing of nutrition interventions. The Government of Tanzania further endorsed the use of Multiple Micronutrient supplements for pregnant women in UNICEF focus region of Mbeya and zanzibar;which will reach ~20,000 pregnant women.;In 2021, 83% (7,256,572) and 97% (238,507) of children 6 – 59 months were supplemented with vitamin A in the Mainland and Zanzibar. | Status:Met | As-of Date:23/12/2021
